Okay - I also went over and verified Collection.undo()
if it returns > 0 it is a card id,  that means get that card, reset, start timer etc.
if it returns -1 that is the specific value that says "do not fetch a new card" (it's commented in there)
if it returns 0 that is either the default or there was a single card reset/reposition/bury
To me this is still confusing to read (why is '-1' important, and why are we only testing if it is not '-1'?) compared with how important it is. We shouldn't require mathematical proofs to know what we're doing
Could you restructure it to explicitly handle the three possible cases with a little comment even though I think one of them ('-1') is a no-op?
Something like this terribly formatted java
if (cid == 0) { /* card schedule change undone, reset and get new card */ Timber.d("Single card non-review change undo succeeded"); }
if (cid > 0) { /* card review undone, set up to review that card again */ Timber.d("Single card review undo succeeded"); }
if (cid < 0) { /* multi-card action undone, no action to take here */ Timber.d("Multi-select undo succeeded"); }
Or anything similar that explained clearly what a return value in each range in the full set of integers means. I recognize I'm asking for something different than was there originally but I think it's an improvement for future explorers in the area, my future self will appreciate it at least
